the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":25,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Wentworth was born about 1265, in Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England, his father, William Wentworth, was 23 and his mother, Beatrice Thakel, was 23. He married Isabella Pollington in 1286, in Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England. He died about 1308, in his hometown, at the age of 45."},"et":{"about 1265–about 1308":"umbes 1265–umbes 1308","1265–1308":"1265–1308","1265–1339":"1265–1339","1270–1319":"1270–1319","1283–1308":"1283–1308","1290–1325":"1290–1325","1244–1308":"1244–1308","1244–1293":"1244–1293","about 1293":"umbes 1293","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1264":"1264","1283":"1283","1293":"1293","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1325":"1325","about 1308":"umbes 1308","1288":"1288","1244":"1244","1265":"1265","about 1265":"umbes 1265","1308":"1308","1319":"1319","1339":"1339","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wentworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England","Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire,